>Speed of electric current in cable ~= 270,000,000 m/s

Right principle but wrong terms. The speed of electric current in an Ethernet cable is closer to the order of 0.1 mm/s, something like half a metre per hour. You've given a value in the order of magnitude of the electric field propagation in an Ethernet cable, not the same thing as speed of the current. In Cat 7 the propagation speed is no more than about 207 Mm/s and for Cat 5 or Cat 6 it's about 195 Mm/s, not 270 Mm/s. It's closer to 0.7c than to the 0.9c you chose. Speed of electricity would have been a better term to use.

I'm not unwilling to, but I don't know if I can teach much as I have absolutely no formal training.

This photo required mainly selection tools, layer masks, color balancing, blur and the eraser.
I used generic stock photos for the source material. Created transparency for the effects with Select -> Color Range and Select -> Modify (think I used Expand and Feather and maybe messed with Levels beforehand) and blended them in with layer mask gradients.
White balance through a mixture of Adjustments -> Levels/Saturation/Color Balance/Brightness.
Lots of manual undo/redo with the brush/eraser and Free Transform.

These are all basic tools needed for any Photoshop job that you can figure out just by messing with the software. Any "skills" I have is just experience to know which menu to open and what knob to adjust to do things efficiently. It's more about knowing a thing is possible so you think to do it rather than the details of the execution, which you can always google a tutorial for and learn something new.

As a kid I picked up CS2 and did a bunch of online tutorials. Not any "beginner's guide to Photoshop" but the internet is full of these "how to create a waterfall/fictional planet/dystopian landscape" type "challenges" that can take anywhere from 5 minutes to a few hours. I recommend doing those just to get comfortable with the software and learning about all the available tools and their possible uses. Fulfilling 4chan requests is an extension of that hobby.

>ext4 handles small files faster than exfat
No it doesn't, it handles them basically the same:
ExFAT - file exists as a "directory entry" that's a tuple of "filename" and a pointer into a linked list of pointers into the disk (that can also be an extent; this is an improvement over FAT32)
Ext4 - file exists as an "inode", that's a short array of pointers into the disk; the last pointer goes to a block on the disk that's basically a larger inode. The inode can also use extents, this is an improvement over ext3.

In either case, allocating a small file means marking a block as used, and creating a directory entry that points to it. On ext3/ext4 you also need to write to an inode, this extra layer is necessary because ext supports hardlinks (FAT also supports hardlinks, but only as a form of filesystem corruption, not as an intended feature).

Are you maybe thinking of NTFS? For small files, NTFS can pack the data stream (which conceptually on NTFS is just another type of metadata, just like the filename) into the directory entry. So on NTFS, a directory with loads of small files in it looks kinda similar to a single medium-sized file.
